# Enumeration in Java

## What is Enumeration (enum)?

-> Enumeration (enum) is a special data type in Java used to define a fixed set of constants.

-> enum stands for Enumerated Type.

-> It is used when a variable can have only a limited number of predefined values.

-> Enumeration improves:
-> Readability
-> Type Safety
-> Maintainability

---

# Why Do We Need Enumeration?

Before enum, developers commonly used:

```java
public static final int MONDAY = 1;
public static final int TUESDAY = 2;
```

Problems:

-> No type safety
-> Any integer value can be passed
-> Difficult to maintain
-> Less readable

---

# Example Without Enum

```java
public class Main {

    public static final int RED = 1;
    public static final int GREEN = 2;
    public static final int BLUE = 3;

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int color = 5;

        System.out.println(color);
    }
}
```

-> Invalid values like 5 are still allowed.

---

# Example With Enum

```java
enum Color {
    RED,
    GREEN,
    BLUE
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Color color = Color.RED;

        System.out.println(color);
    }
}
```

Output:

```text
RED
```

---

# Important Observation

```java
Color.RED
```

-> RED is not a normal variable.

-> It is an enum constant.

-> Java internally creates objects for enum constants.

---

# Internal Understanding

Java internally behaves somewhat like this:

```java
final class Color {

    public static final Color RED = new Color();
    public static final Color GREEN = new Color();
    public static final Color BLUE = new Color();
}
```

-> Constructor is controlled internally by Java.

