# Enum and Singleton

Enum is one of the best ways to implement Singleton.

Example:

```java
public enum EnumSingleton {

    INSTANCE;

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Singleton Method");
    }
}
```

Usage:

```java
EnumSingleton.INSTANCE.show();
```

---

# Why Enum Singleton Is Special

-> Thread-safe by default

-> Prevents reflection attacks

-> Prevents serialization issues

-> Simplest Singleton implementation

---

# Memory Understanding

```text
JVM Loads Enum
      ↓
Enum Constants Created Once
      ↓
Shared Everywhere
```

---

# Important Characteristics of Enum

-> Enum constants are static and final internally.

-> Enum can have:
-> Variables
-> Constructors
-> Methods

-> Enum cannot extend another class because it already extends java.lang.Enum.

-> Enum can implement interfaces.

---

# Enum Implementing Interface

Example:

```java
interface Printable {
    void print();
}


enum Demo implements Printable {

    TEST;

    @Override
    public void print() {
        System.out.println("Printing");
    }
}
```

---

# Enum vs Normal Constants

| Normal Constants             | Enum                     |
| ---------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| Not type-safe                | Type-safe                |
| Uses primitive/static values | Uses enum constants      |
| Less readable                | More readable            |
| Difficult to maintain        | Easier to maintain       |
| Invalid values possible      | Invalid values prevented |

